<p><strong>Assignments</strong></p>

<p>Every assignment would be delivered in five versions: A three page version, a one page version, a three paragraph version, a one paragraph version, and a one sentence version.</p>

<p>Along the way youâ€™d trade detail for brevity. Hopefully adding clarity at each point.  Each step requires asking â€œWhatâ€™s really important?â€ Thatâ€™s the most important question you can ask yourself about anything. The class would really be about answering that very question at each step of the way. Whittling it all down until all thatâ€™s left is the point.</p>

<p>Try this:</p>

<p>Draft a piece in your usual way. Save a copy.
Delete 1/10 of the paragraphs. This may remove important ideas. Thatâ€™s okay. Weâ€™ll restore those (or try to) in step 6. When calculating 1/10, round up. That is, if you start with fifteen paragraphs, delete two and not one.
Delete 1/10 of the remaining sentences.
Delete 1/10 of the remaining words.
Note the number of words in the thrice decimated piece. This is your word count limit.
Revise to restore any essential ideas that were lost in steps 2â€“4, but do not exceed the word count limit from step 5.
My writerâ€™s group did this exercise. It was excruciating. But it was worth the pain. Everyoneâ€™s writing came to life.</p>

<p>Some things youâ€™ll learn:</p>

<p>Your patterns and habits that add unnecessary words. Maybe youâ€™ll learn that you overuse â€œto beâ€ verbs, or insert too many weasel words, such as â€œperhapsâ€ or â€œsomehowâ€.
How to find strong verbs and nouns that do all the work of multiple weaker words.
How to identify and emphasize the essence of what you are trying to say, and prioritize what to include and what to exclude.</p>

